      <h2>Battery</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Recharge only with the charger specified for the battery. For specific charging instructions, read the operator's manual supplied with your charger and battery.
      </div>

      <h3>Removing and Inserting the Battery</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>To insert:</strong> slide the M12&trade; battery pack into the body of the tool until it latches securely into place.</li>
        <li><strong>To remove:</strong> push in the release buttons and pull the battery pack away from the tool.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="note">
        Always lock the trigger or remove the battery pack any time the tool is not in use, and before making any adjustments or changing accessories.
      </div>

      <h2>Shavings Collection</h2>

      <p>To keep the workplace cleaner, connect the planer to a running vacuum while you work.</p>

      <ol>
        <li>Switch the shavings diverter to the left or right, depending on the job.</li>
        <li>Slide the included shavings collection attachment onto the planer until it clicks into place.</li>
        <li>Attach the included vacuum port to the collection attachment by pushing down on the lever on the vacuum adapter.</li>
        <li>Push a vacuum hose (1-1/4&quot;, 1-7/8&quot;, or 2-1/2&quot; diameter) onto the vacuum port.</li>
        <li>To remove: pull the hose off the vacuum port, push the lever on the adapter, and pull it free of the collection attachment.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="note">
        If you are <em>not</em> using the shavings collection option, do not run the planer with the collection attachment installed. At the end of each project, remove the battery, then clear the shavings ejection area with a non-marring (non-metallic) object such as the blunt end of a pencil, and vacuum out any remaining debris.
      </div>

      <h2>Installing and Replacing Blades</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Blades are sharp and fragile &mdash; handle with care. Always change or reverse blades in pairs. Unpaired blades can cause increased vibration, loss of control, and lower tool performance. Use only 2-1/4&quot; tungsten-carbide, double-edged (reversible) planer blades. Do not sharpen planer blades &mdash; reverse them when one cutting edge becomes dull or chipped.
      </div>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/milwaukee-2524-20/blade-install.png" alt="Close-up of the planer blade drum showing the blade clamp and the three blade bolts that secure each blade" />
        <figcaption>The blade drum carries two blades, each held by a blade clamp and three blade bolts</figcaption>
      </div>

      <h3>To Remove Blades</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Remove the battery pack.</li>
        <li>Clean dust and debris from the blade drum.</li>
        <li>Using the supplied 1/8&quot; hex wrench, loosen (do not remove) the three blade bolts.</li>
        <li>Using a scrap piece of wood, slide the old blade out of the blade clamp. If it is difficult to remove, clean the blade and clamp with alcohol, mineral spirits, or lacquer thinner.</li>
        <li>Rotate the blade drum and repeat for the other blade.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>To Install Blades</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Remove the battery pack.</li>
        <li>Reverse the existing blades or fit new ones.</li>
        <li>Align the groove on the top of the blade with the ridge of the blade clamp and carefully slide the blade onto the drum.</li>
        <li>Center the blade lengthwise &mdash; it will overhang the blade clamp slightly on both sides.</li>
        <li>Using a block of wood, push the blade back toward the blade clamp so its inner side is pressed against the step on the drum. This ensures proper alignment, reducing vibration and keeping the depth of cut accurate.</li>
        <li>Using a torque wrench, tighten all three blade bolts to <strong>19 in. lb.</strong></li>
        <li>Verify the torque of all bolts again now that the blade is secured.</li>
        <li>Rotate the blade drum and repeat for the other blade.</li>
        <li>Once installed, rotate the blade drum to confirm the blades do not contact the shoe or housing and that both blades are installed straight.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="warning">
        Improperly tightened blade bolts can result in loosened blades, which could cause injury or damage to the tool or workpiece.
      </div>

      <h2>Adjusting the Depth of Cut</h2>

      <ol>
        <li>Remove the battery pack.</li>
        <li>Determine how much material to remove per pass, accounting for the moisture and hardness of the workpiece and the desired feed rate.</li>
        <li>Each detent equals 1/256&quot;. Turn the knob <strong>clockwise to increase</strong> the depth of cut and <strong>counterclockwise to decrease</strong> it. Do not change the depth of cut while planing.</li>
        <li>Make a test cut. If the planer moves easily through the workpiece, increase the depth; if it seems to strain, decrease the depth.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Closing the Kickstand</h3>
      <p>The kickstand protects the blade when the tool is set down. It is pushed up automatically during normal planing. To close it manually, push it closed and slide it to the side.</p>

      <h2>Operation</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Always wear eye protection marked to comply with ANSI Z87.1. When working in dusty conditions, wear respiratory protection or use an OSHA-compliant dust extraction solution.
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li>Remove the battery pack.</li>
        <li>Check the blades and replace if necessary.</li>
        <li>Turn the shavings diverter to the desired side. Install the vacuum on the appropriate side if desired (only attach the collection attachment if using dust collection).</li>
        <li>Adjust the depth of cut based on the amount of material to remove.</li>
        <li>Clamp the work securely.</li>
        <li>Insert the battery pack.</li>
        <li>Grasp the tool firmly by the handle and the depth adjustment knob.</li>
        <li>Line up the front of the tool with the workpiece. <strong>Without</strong> contacting the blade drum to the workpiece, press the trigger lock-off and pull the trigger. Wait for the tool to reach full speed before beginning, to avoid overloading and damaging it.</li>
        <li>Keeping the front shoe flush with the workpiece, use gentle pressure to guide the planer. All pressure should be on the front shoe when starting the cut; transfer downward pressure to the rear shoe as it contacts the workpiece. Too much pressure produces uneven planing.</li>
        <li>Push the planer through the workpiece at an even rate. Do not push too fast &mdash; it strains the motor and can damage the blades. Never pull the planer backward over the workpiece.</li>
        <li>When the pass is finished, lift the planer away from the workpiece and wait for the blade to stop completely before setting it down.</li>
        <li>Continue with progressive cuts until near the desired depth, then set the knob to a very shallow depth for the final passes to ensure a smooth finish.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="note">
        <strong>Feed rate vs. finish:</strong> slow feed + shallow depth of cut = smooth finish; faster feed + deep depth of cut = rough finish. If the chute becomes clogged, remove the battery pack before clearing all dust and debris &mdash; keep hands and fingers away from the dust chute.
      </div>

      <h3>Types of Cuts</h3>

      <h4>Rabbeting / Shiplapping</h4>
      <p>A step cut achieved with repetitive passes. Align the blade edge with the cutting line, slide the planer along the workpiece at an even rate, and repeat until the desired depth is reached. Maximum rabbeting depth is 7/10&quot;; maximum rabbeting width is 2-1/5&quot;.</p>

      <h4>Chamfering</h4>
      <p>An angle cut. Align the chamfer groove in the front shoe with the edge of the workpiece at the desired angle, slide the planer along the workpiece at an even rate, and repeat until the desired chamfer is reached.</p>

      <h2>Maintenance</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Always remove the battery pack before performing any maintenance. Never disassemble the tool, battery pack, or charger &mdash; contact a Milwaukee service facility for all repairs.
      </div>

      <ul>
        <li>Adopt a regular maintenance program. Inspect for undue noise, misalignment or binding of moving parts, breakage, or any other condition affecting operation.</li>
        <li>After six months to one year of use, return the tool, battery pack, and charger to a Milwaukee service facility for inspection.</li>
        <li>If the tool will not start or run at full power with a fully charged battery, clean the battery pack contacts. If it still misbehaves, return it for repair.</li>
        <li><strong>Cleaning:</strong> clear dust and debris from the vents. Keep the tool clean, dry, and free of oil or grease. Use only mild soap and a damp cloth &mdash; never gasoline, turpentine, lacquer thinner, paint thinner, chlorinated solvents, ammonia, or ammonia-based detergents, and never flammable or combustible solvents.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="danger">
        Never immerse the tool, battery pack, or charger in liquid or allow liquid to flow inside them.
      </div>

      <h2>Troubleshooting</h2>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Symptom</th><th>Likely cause / remedy</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Excessive vibration or &ldquo;wobble&rdquo;</td><td>Blades unpaired, improperly aligned, or bolts not torqued to 19 in. lb. Recheck blade installation and bolt torque.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Uneven / snipe planing</td><td>Too much downward pressure, or pressure not transferred from front shoe to rear shoe. Use gentle, even pressure.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Rough finish</td><td>Feed rate too fast or depth of cut too deep. Reduce depth and slow the feed; use shallow final passes.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Motor strains / planer hard to push</td><td>Depth of cut too deep for the material. Decrease the depth of cut.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Chute clogged</td><td>Remove the battery pack and clear dust and debris &mdash; keep fingers away from the dust chute.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Tool will not start or lacks power</td><td>Confirm battery is charged and seated; clean the battery contacts. If unresolved, return to a Milwaukee service facility.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

